com.apriori.collections

Class SortedArraySet<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.apriori.collections.SortedArraySet<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of element in the set
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Iterable<E>, java.util.Collection<E>, java.util.NavigableSet<E>, java.util.Set<E>, java.util.SortedSet<E>

    public class SortedArraySet<E>
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.util.NavigableSet<E>, java.lang.Cloneable, java.io.Serializable
    An implementation of NavigableSet that is optimized for memory efficiency at the cost of slower mutations. This is ideal for representing very large sets that do not change. Smaller sets that change infrequently is another good use case.

    This set uses an array internally to store the items in the set. Lookups are O(log2n). Due to the way the elements are stored in the array, mutations (insertions and removals) can involve O(n) operations to shuffle elements around.

    This set only supports null values when using a Comparator that can compare null values.

    • Field Detail

      • modCount

        protected transient int modCount
        The set's current revision level. Every modification to the set causes this count to be incremented. It is used to implement the "fail-fast" behavior for detecting concurrent modifications to the set.

      • trimToSize

        public void trimToSize()
        Shrinks the internal array so that it is exactly the necessary size. Attempts to add an item to the set after this is called will cause it to grow the internal array to fit the new item.
